A Performance Analysis Engineer for GPU Profiling and Optimization is a specialized role focused on identifying bottlenecks and enhancing the efficiency of software running on Graphics Processing Units. These engineers bridge the gap between high-level application code and low-level hardware architecture to maximize "Performance per Watt". 
Kempner Computing Handbook

Core Responsibilities
GPU Profiling: Using tools like NVIDIA Nsight Systems (system-wide analysis) and Nsight Compute (kernel-specific details) to trace execution and identify hotspots.
Bottleneck Identification: Pinpointing whether an application is limited by compute (math operations), memory bandwidth, or communication overhead (e.g., PCIe or NVLink transfers).
Optimization: Implementing techniques such as kernel fusion, memory pinning, and reducing precision (e.g., from FP32 to FP16) to speed up execution.
Tool Development: Designing and prototyping new data collection methods and profiling libraries to support next-generation GPU architectures. 

Key Skills & Requirements
Programming: Mastery of C/C++ and scripting languages like Python for automation.
GPU APIs: Deep knowledge of parallel computing frameworks such as NVIDIA CUDA, OpenCL, or Vulkan.
Architecture Knowledge: Understanding of SM (Streaming Multiprocessor) utilization, memory hierarchies (L1/L2 caches, HBM), and hardware performance counters.
Experience: Typically requires a BS/MS/PhD in Computer Engineering or CS, with 2+ years of experience in system software or device drivers. 

Industry Context
Major tech companies like NVIDIA, AMD, Qualcomm, and Apple hire for these roles to optimize workloads ranging from AI/LLM training to mobile gaming and autonomous driving. 

