SKILLS & tools required
To excel as a Performance Analysis Engineer for GPU Profiling and Optimization, you need a combination of low-level hardware knowledge and proficiency with vendor-specific toolchains.
1. Essential Profiling & Debugging Tools
Mastering these tools is critical for identifying bottlenecks across different hardware vendors:
NVIDIA Stack: Use Nsight Systems for system-wide timeline tracing and Nsight Compute for deep-dive kernel-level metrics. For correctness and memory leak detection, use Compute Sanitizer.
AMD Stack: Utilize the Radeon Developer Tool Suite, specifically the Radeon GPU Profiler (RGP) for instruction-level traces and AMD uProf for system-wide performance and power analysis.
Cross-Platform & Open Source: HPCToolkit and TAU (Tuning and Analysis Utility) are vital for vendor-neutral profiling across NVIDIA, AMD, and Intel GPUs.
Graphics-Specific: For gaming or rendering workloads, tools like RenderDoc and Nsight Graphics allow for frame-by-frame capture and shader debugging. 

2. Core Technical Skills
GPU Architectures: Deep understanding of Streaming Multiprocessors (SMs), warp/wavefront scheduling, memory hierarchies (L1/L2, HBM, DDR), and interconnects like NVLink.
Parallel Programming: Proficiency in NVIDIA CUDA, ROCm/HIP, or graphics APIs like Vulkan and DirectX 12.
Software Development: Strong C/C++ for writing performance-critical code and Python for automating data collection and analysis scripts.
Data Analysis: Ability to interpret complex telemetry data, including hardware performance counters (e.g., occupancy, stall reasons, memory throughput) to propose novel optimization strategies. 

3. Specialized Libraries & Frameworks
Communication: Knowledge of distributed training libraries like NCCL (NVIDIA) or RCCL (AMD) for multi-GPU scaling.
AI/ML Frameworks: Familiarity with PyTorch and TensorFlow profiling extensions (e.g., PyTorch Kineto) to optimize large-scale AI training workloads. 

